00:16:37.376 --> 00:16:39.286 A:middle
This stream can come in two

00:16:39.286 --> 00:16:41.836 A:middle
forms of data, disparity or

00:16:41.836 --> 00:16:42.166 A:middle
depth.

00:16:42.846 --> 00:16:44.306 A:middle
Now disparity is the inverse of

00:16:44.306 --> 00:16:46.586 A:middle
depth and vice versa, so which

00:16:46.586 --> 00:16:47.396 A:middle
one should you choose?

00:16:48.666 --> 00:16:51.366 A:middle
Well disparity usually yields

00:16:51.366 --> 00:16:53.456 A:middle
better results, especially for

00:16:53.456 --> 00:16:54.596 A:middle
machine learning applications

00:16:55.216 --> 00:16:56.646 A:middle
but the depth data has more

00:16:56.646 --> 00:16:58.346 A:middle
meaning in terms of real-world

00:16:58.346 --> 00:16:58.926 A:middle
measurements.

00:17:00.036 --> 00:17:01.666 A:middle
Know that if you work with depth

00:17:01.746 --> 00:17:05.246 A:middle
that the depth error goes with

00:17:05.246 --> 00:17:05.935 A:middle
the depth squared.

00:17:06.036 --> 00:17:08.096 A:middle
That means that an object at 1

00:17:08.096 --> 00:17:09.685 A:middle
meter would have four times the

00:17:09.685 --> 00:17:11.826 A:middle
depth accuracy as an object at 2

00:17:11.826 --> 00:17:11.976 A:middle
meters.

00:17:16.286 --> 00:17:18.496 A:middle
We have two streams, video and

00:17:18.496 --> 00:17:19.425 A:middle
depth, and they don't

00:17:19.425 --> 00:17:20.596 A:middle
necessarily share the same

00:17:20.596 --> 00:17:21.136 A:middle
resolution.

00:17:21.646 --> 00:17:23.006 A:middle
The native resolution of the

00:17:23.006 --> 00:17:24.596 A:middle
TrueDepth's camera is VGA or

00:17:24.596 --> 00:17:27.736 A:middle
640x480 and that's what you'll

00:17:27.736 --> 00:17:30.176 A:middle
get if you choose a video preset

00:17:30.656 --> 00:17:32.236 A:middle
of an aspect racial of 4:3.

00:17:33.226 --> 00:17:35.516 A:middle
If however you choose an aspect

00:17:35.516 --> 00:17:37.816 A:middle
ratio of 16x9 you'll get a depth

00:17:37.816 --> 00:17:40.246 A:middle
map of 640x360.

00:17:40.966 --> 00:17:42.916 A:middle
In both cases the depth map will

00:17:42.916 --> 00:17:44.856 A:middle
cover the entire field of view

00:17:45.146 --> 00:17:46.146 A:middle
of the RGB image.

00:17:46.666 --> 00:17:49.466 A:middle
Now we are talking about video

00:17:49.466 --> 00:17:51.116 A:middle
applications, so we are

00:17:51.116 --> 00:17:52.946 A:middle
crunching a lot of numbers very,

00:17:52.946 --> 00:17:54.956 A:middle
very fast and that could create

00:17:55.306 --> 00:17:57.266 A:middle
system pressure over time.

00:17:57.936 --> 00:17:59.696 A:middle
So you can test your application

00:17:59.696 --> 00:18:01.306 A:middle
and gauge the system pressure

00:17:59.696 --> 00:18:01.306 A:middle
and gauge the system pressure

00:18:01.306 --> 00:18:04.006 A:middle
level which goes from nominal to

00:18:04.006 --> 00:18:06.216 A:middle
fair, serious, critical, and

00:18:06.216 --> 00:18:07.056 A:middle
then shutdown.

00:18:07.476 --> 00:18:08.956 A:middle
And the responsibility is in

00:18:08.956 --> 00:18:10.886 A:middle
your hands because the system

00:18:11.166 --> 00:18:12.326 A:middle
will let you go all the way to

00:18:12.326 --> 00:18:15.206 A:middle
shutdown but when it does it's

00:18:15.206 --> 00:18:17.326 A:middle
bye-bye every capture device.

00:18:17.726 --> 00:18:22.026 A:middle
Another thing you can do is to

00:18:22.026 --> 00:18:24.006 A:middle
adopt a degradation scheme, if

00:18:24.006 --> 00:18:25.496 A:middle
the pressure level gets serious

00:18:25.496 --> 00:18:27.206 A:middle
you can reduce the frame rate to

00:18:27.206 --> 00:18:29.736 A:middle
15 frames per second or you can

00:18:29.736 --> 00:18:31.516 A:middle
choose a more elaborate scheme

00:18:31.896 --> 00:18:33.966 A:middle
with gentle degradation going

00:18:33.966 --> 00:18:37.356 A:middle
from 30, 24, 20 and 15 frames

00:18:37.356 --> 00:18:39.536 A:middle
per second anytime the pressure

00:18:39.536 --> 00:18:39.976 A:middle
level increases.

00:18:43.836 --> 00:18:45.026 A:middle
So we have holes in the depth

00:18:45.026 --> 00:18:46.406 A:middle
map what can we do about it?

00:18:47.686 --> 00:18:49.456 A:middle
Well, in fact you could get the

00:18:49.456 --> 00:18:51.496 A:middle
stream already filtered for you.

00:18:52.176 --> 00:18:53.936 A:middle
There is a parameter called

00:18:53.936 --> 00:18:55.546 A:middle
isFilteringEnabled and it's'

00:18:55.546 --> 00:18:57.676 A:middle
defaulted to true, which means

00:18:57.676 --> 00:18:59.236 A:middle
you get a filtered depth map

00:18:59.606 --> 00:19:01.576 A:middle
smooth, spatially and temporally

00:18:59.606 --> 00:19:01.576 A:middle
smooth, spatially and temporally

00:19:01.776 --> 00:19:03.536 A:middle
and the holes are filled from

00:19:03.536 --> 00:19:04.356 A:middle
the RGB image.

00:19:05.466 --> 00:19:07.256 A:middle
This is especially useful for

00:19:07.256 --> 00:19:08.616 A:middle
photography and segmentation

00:19:08.616 --> 00:19:10.206 A:middle
applications because you know

00:19:10.446 --> 00:19:12.386 A:middle
every time you query a pixel you

00:19:12.386 --> 00:19:13.216 A:middle
get the depth's value.

00:19:13.776 --> 00:19:17.376 A:middle
In TrueDepth Streamer you can

00:19:17.376 --> 00:19:19.566 A:middle
switch to the filter stream and

00:19:19.566 --> 00:19:21.876 A:middle
see that it is smoother and the

00:19:21.876 --> 00:19:22.586 A:middle
holes are filled.

00:19:23.126 --> 00:19:27.526 A:middle
So this is great, but it is not

00:19:27.526 --> 00:19:29.246 A:middle
applicable to 100% of the use

00:19:29.246 --> 00:19:29.636 A:middle
cases.

00:19:30.226 --> 00:19:31.676 A:middle
If you're working with point

00:19:31.676 --> 00:19:34.606 A:middle
clouds or any type of real-world

00:19:34.836 --> 00:19:36.256 A:middle
measurements you're better off

00:19:36.256 --> 00:19:38.366 A:middle
staying with the raw data which

00:19:38.366 --> 00:19:39.806 A:middle
holds the highest fidelity.

00:19:40.846 --> 00:19:42.726 A:middle
If you do you will have holes,

00:19:42.906 --> 00:19:44.496 A:middle
you will have pixels marked as

00:19:44.496 --> 00:19:46.866 A:middle
zero, it does not mean that they

00:19:46.866 --> 00:19:48.396 A:middle
are the distance of zero meters

00:19:48.396 --> 00:19:50.356 A:middle
from the camera it just means we

00:19:50.356 --> 00:19:52.296 A:middle
have no information about them.

00:19:53.336 --> 00:19:54.946 A:middle
Therefore, you should watch out

00:19:55.116 --> 00:19:56.506 A:middle
for operations like averaging

00:19:56.506 --> 00:19:57.606 A:middle
and downsampling because you

00:19:57.606 --> 00:19:59.386 A:middle
don't want to mix those real

00:19:59.386 --> 00:20:00.976 A:middle
values with those zeros.

00:19:59.386 --> 00:20:00.976 A:middle
values with those zeros.

00:20:03.756 --> 00:20:04.996 A:middle
But why do we even get holes?

00:20:05.536 --> 00:20:08.876 A:middle
Well the TrueDepth camera

00:20:09.296 --> 00:20:11.456 A:middle
detects objects up to a distance

00:20:11.456 --> 00:20:14.056 A:middle
of about 5 meters, but not all

00:20:14.056 --> 00:20:15.296 A:middle
materials are made the same.

00:20:15.636 --> 00:20:16.796 A:middle
Some materials have low

00:20:16.796 --> 00:20:17.496 A:middle
reflectivity.

00:20:17.716 --> 00:20:20.126 A:middle
they absorb most of the lights.

00:20:21.476 --> 00:20:23.656 A:middle
For example this extreme

00:20:23.706 --> 00:20:26.046 A:middle
scenario is a very low

00:20:26.046 --> 00:20:27.896 A:middle
reflective fabric watch what

00:20:27.896 --> 00:20:29.686 A:middle
happens when we switch to the

00:20:29.686 --> 00:20:31.766 A:middle
depth map and I walk away from

00:20:33.346 --> 00:20:33.436 A:middle
it.

00:20:33.696 --> 00:20:35.066 A:middle
Even though there are objects in

00:20:35.066 --> 00:20:37.466 A:middle
the scene with larger distance

00:20:37.796 --> 00:20:39.866 A:middle
we see holes forming on this

00:20:39.866 --> 00:20:41.436 A:middle
fabric because it's absorbing

00:20:42.026 --> 00:20:42.766 A:middle
most of the light.

00:20:44.126 --> 00:20:45.446 A:middle
If we switch to the filtered

00:20:45.446 --> 00:20:47.616 A:middle
stream and repeat the same

00:20:47.616 --> 00:20:49.246 A:middle
motion those holes are filled.

00:20:49.786 --> 00:20:53.336 A:middle
But it's not only about the

00:20:53.336 --> 00:20:54.766 A:middle
amount of light reflected back

00:20:55.326 --> 00:20:56.916 A:middle
it's also about the direction in

00:20:56.916 --> 00:20:58.056 A:middle
which it is reflected to.

00:20:59.116 --> 00:21:01.036 A:middle
Some materials are specular or

00:20:59.116 --> 00:21:01.036 A:middle
Some materials are specular or

00:21:01.036 --> 00:21:02.826 A:middle
shiny and they are very picky

00:21:02.826 --> 00:21:04.166 A:middle
and choosy in which direction

00:21:04.166 --> 00:21:05.046 A:middle
they send back the light.

00:21:05.656 --> 00:21:08.406 A:middle
An extreme scenario would be

00:21:08.406 --> 00:21:11.816 A:middle
this display, you can watch the

00:21:11.816 --> 00:21:12.846 A:middle
video stream to see the

00:21:12.846 --> 00:21:13.436 A:middle
reflection.

00:21:14.616 --> 00:21:15.746 A:middle
And when we switch to the depth

00:21:15.746 --> 00:21:18.366 A:middle
map holes are forming depending

00:21:18.366 --> 00:21:19.746 A:middle
on the angle between the device

00:21:19.746 --> 00:21:20.246 A:middle
and the screen.

00:21:21.556 --> 00:21:23.376 A:middle
And if we switch to the filtered

00:21:23.376 --> 00:21:25.216 A:middle
stream those holes are filled

00:21:25.666 --> 00:21:26.976 A:middle
but with less fidelity.

00:21:31.046 --> 00:21:32.916 A:middle
Another challenging scenario is

00:21:32.916 --> 00:21:35.306 A:middle
outdoor, typically in an outdoor

00:21:35.306 --> 00:21:36.996 A:middle
scene the background is very far

00:21:36.996 --> 00:21:38.736 A:middle
away so we don't expect to get

00:21:38.736 --> 00:21:39.806 A:middle
any depth on the background.

00:21:40.456 --> 00:21:42.956 A:middle
Also, the sun acts as an

00:21:42.956 --> 00:21:44.396 A:middle
aggressor to the active

00:21:44.396 --> 00:21:44.906 A:middle
illumination.

00:21:45.496 --> 00:21:48.696 A:middle
To demonstrate that I went

00:21:48.696 --> 00:21:50.006 A:middle
outside on a very sunny

00:21:50.006 --> 00:21:51.556 A:middle
afternoon, positioned myself

00:21:51.556 --> 00:21:52.326 A:middle
against the sun.

00:21:53.216 --> 00:21:54.286 A:middle
And when we switch to the depth

00:21:54.286 --> 00:21:55.926 A:middle
map you can see there's no

00:21:55.926 --> 00:21:58.056 A:middle
depths on the background and we

00:21:58.056 --> 00:21:59.786 A:middle
get some holes around the

00:21:59.786 --> 00:22:01.726 A:middle
frames, specifically in this

00:21:59.786 --> 00:22:01.726 A:middle
frames, specifically in this

00:22:01.726 --> 00:22:02.506 A:middle
case the hair.

00:22:03.476 --> 00:22:05.556 A:middle
But still most of the depth on

00:22:05.556 --> 00:22:07.126 A:middle
the foreground is intact and

00:22:07.126 --> 00:22:07.696 A:middle
very useful.

00:22:08.256 --> 00:22:12.436 A:middle
One final point I want to cover

00:22:12.596 --> 00:22:14.616 A:middle
for getting holes is the fact

00:22:14.616 --> 00:22:15.736 A:middle
that from the perspective of the

00:22:15.736 --> 00:22:17.516 A:middle
TrueDepth camera some of the

00:22:17.516 --> 00:22:19.396 A:middle
light projected hits an object

00:22:19.396 --> 00:22:21.306 A:middle
on the way back so we get

00:22:21.306 --> 00:22:23.006 A:middle
shadows from the parallax

00:22:23.006 --> 00:22:24.886 A:middle
between the projector and the

00:22:25.776 --> 00:22:26.096 A:middle
camera.

00:22:26.096 --> 00:22:27.316 A:middle
You can see an example on the

00:22:27.316 --> 00:22:29.266 A:middle
right side of this mug, but

00:22:30.176 --> 00:22:31.576 A:middle
something is different here.

00:22:32.676 --> 00:22:34.426 A:middle
This is not a depth map so why

00:22:34.426 --> 00:22:36.916 A:middle
do we even get holes?

00:22:37.096 --> 00:22:38.586 A:middle
Well in TrueDepth Streamer you

00:22:38.586 --> 00:22:41.076 A:middle
can switch from 2-D mode into

00:22:41.076 --> 00:22:43.136 A:middle
3-D mode, which gives us a point

00:22:43.136 --> 00:22:43.616 A:middle
cloud view.

00:22:44.326 --> 00:22:45.956 A:middle
With point clouds we can

00:22:45.956 --> 00:22:47.426 A:middle
dynamically change the

00:22:47.426 --> 00:22:48.936 A:middle
perspective of the scene

00:22:50.796 --> 00:22:53.506 A:middle
creating even more holes when we

00:22:54.106 --> 00:22:56.256 A:middle
do so.

00:22:56.396 --> 00:22:58.226 A:middle
And now I can ask you is this

00:22:58.226 --> 00:23:01.706 A:middle
mug half empty or half full and

00:22:58.226 --> 00:23:01.706 A:middle
mug half empty or half full and

00:23:01.706 --> 00:23:03.826 A:middle
the answer is we have no idea.

00:23:05.256 --> 00:23:07.176 A:middle
By virtually changing the point

00:23:07.176 --> 00:23:08.606 A:middle
of view of the camera we don't

00:23:08.606 --> 00:23:10.696 A:middle
add new information and that is

00:23:10.696 --> 00:23:11.966 A:middle
because the TrueDepth camera can

00:23:11.966 --> 00:23:13.656 A:middle
do many things, but bending

00:23:13.656 --> 00:23:16.466 A:middle
light into the mug not one of

00:23:17.556 --> 00:23:17.726 A:middle
them.

00:23:18.076 --> 00:23:18.786 A:middle
Let's see this live.

00:23:21.516 --> 00:23:24.500 A:middle
